train <- window(data, start=c(1971,1), end=c(1979,12))
test <- window(data, start=c(1980,1), end=c(1980,12))
  1. Plot the training dataset. Is Box-Cox transformation necessary for this data?
# Make a time plot 
autoplot(train)

tsdisplay(train)

Yes, the Box-Cox transformation is necessary. The graph shows a little bit changing in variantion as the level of the series increases. Thus, we need the Box-Cox transformation to stabilize the variance.

We can also verify this using the boxcox.lambda() to check:

lambda <- BoxCox.lambda(train)
lambda
## [1] -0.3944237

Since the lambda is not equal to 1, we need to transform our data slightly:

train %>% BoxCox(lambda = lambda) %>% tsdisplay()

  1. Is the training dataset stationary? If not, find an appropriate differencing which yields seasonal and trend stationary training dataset. Plot the ACF and PACF to determine if the detrended and deseasonalized time series is stationary.
tsdisplay(train)

From the graph above, we can see there are apparent spikes in 1, 12, 24 Thus, the training dataset is not stationary. After finding the appropriate differencing, we get:

tsdisplay(diff(diff(train,lag = 12)),main='Monthly Condmilk')

kpss.test(diff(diff(train, lag = 12)))
## Warning in kpss.test(diff(diff(train, lag = 12))): p-value greater than printed
## p-value
## 
##  KPSS Test for Level Stationarity
## 
## data:  diff(diff(train, lag = 12))
## KPSS Level = 0.033903, Truncation lag parameter = 3, p-value = 0.1

From the graph above, we can see that by doing diff(diff(train,lag = 12), we did deseasonalize the time series and get stationary data, both proved by acf graph(no obvious seasonality) and kpss.test(p-value > 0.05, cannot reject the null hypothesis).

  1. Build two (,,)(,,) models using the training dataset and auto.arima() function.
# Model 1: Let the auto.arima() function determine the best order of non-seasonal and seasonal differencing.
fit1 <- auto.arima(train,seasonal=TRUE)
fit1 # model=ARIMA(1,0,0)(2,1,0)[12],  AICc=766.11
## Series: train 
## ARIMA(1,0,0)(2,1,0)[12] 
## 
## Coefficients:
##          ar1     sar1     sar2
##       0.7625  -0.7745  -0.5032
## s.e.  0.0676   0.1007   0.0989
## 
## sigma^2 estimated as 143.5:  log likelihood=-378.83
## AIC=765.67   AICc=766.11   BIC=775.93
# Model 2: Set the order of seasonal-differencing d to 1 and D to 1
fit2 <- auto.arima(train, d=1, D=1)
fit2 # model=ARIMA(0,1,0)(2,1,0)[12],  AICc=767.42
## Series: train 
## ARIMA(0,1,1)(2,1,0)[12] 
## 
## Coefficients:
##           ma1     sar1     sar2
##       -0.1672  -0.7597  -0.4931
## s.e.   0.1104   0.1004   0.0997
## 
## sigma^2 estimated as 160:  log likelihood=-379.49
## AIC=766.98   AICc=767.42   BIC=777.19
comp_aicc <- rbind(fit1$aicc, fit2$aicc)
comp_bic <- rbind(fit1$aicc, fit2$aicc)
comp <- cbind(comp_aicc, comp_bic)
rownames(comp) <- c('sarima d=0', 'sarima d=1')
colnames(comp) <- c('aicc', 'bic')
comp
##                aicc      bic
## sarima d=0 766.1072 766.1072
## sarima d=1 767.4236 767.4236

Between the two seasonal arima models, ARIMA(1,0,0)(2,1,0)[12] has lower aicc and bic scores. This suggests that we need not necessarily to set the seasonal-differencing to be 1.

  1. Plot the residuals ACF of both models from part 4 and use the Ljung-Box Test with lag 12 to verify your conclusion.
checkresiduals(fit1,lag=12)

## 
##  Ljung-Box test
## 
## data:  Residuals from ARIMA(1,0,0)(2,1,0)[12]
## Q* = 16.366, df = 9, p-value = 0.05963
## 
## Model df: 3.   Total lags used: 12
Box.test(fit1$residuals, lag = 12, type =  "Ljung-Box")
## 
##  Box-Ljung test
## 
## data:  fit1$residuals
## X-squared = 16.366, df = 12, p-value = 0.1751
checkresiduals(fit2,lag=12)

## 
##  Ljung-Box test
## 
## data:  Residuals from ARIMA(0,1,1)(2,1,0)[12]
## Q* = 14.81, df = 9, p-value = 0.09629
## 
## Model df: 3.   Total lags used: 12
Box.test(fit2$residuals, lag = 12, type =  "Ljung-Box")
## 
##  Box-Ljung test
## 
## data:  fit2$residuals
## X-squared = 14.81, df = 12, p-value = 0.252

From the results above, we can see that the residuals: have 0 mean, with normal distribution(although slightly left skew), with acf having no statistical significance. It can be proved that the residuals are white noise. Also, the Box-Ljung test shows that p > 0.05, representing fail to reject the null hypothesis. Thus, it further verifies my conclusion.

  1. Compare the forecast with the actual test data by calculating the Mean Absolute Percentage Error (MAPE) and Mean Squared Error (MSE). Which model is better to forecast the Manufacturers Stocks for each month of 1980 (i.e., Jan, Feb, , Dec)?
MAPE <- MAPE(predict_fit1$mean, test)
MAPE2 <- MAPE(predict_fit2$mean, test)
MSE <- MSE(predict_fit1$mean, test)
MSE2 <- MSE(predict_fit2$mean, test)
Eval <- cbind(c(MAPE, MAPE2), c(MSE, MSE2))
colnames(Eval) <- c('MAPE', 'MSE')
rownames(Eval) <- c('d=0', 'd=1')
Eval
##          MAPE      MSE
## d=0 0.1842871 309.5345
## d=1 0.1975673 352.8060

Model d=0(without seasonal-differencing) is better to forecast the Manufacturers Stocks for each month of 1980. They have similar MAPE values but d=0 model has apparently smaller MSE value.
